    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-12-05T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-12-05T01:00:00-05:00" n="292"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d292">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/1027: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-12-05T13:00:00+07:00"
                            >December 5, 1942—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 2:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1439. For the Secretary and Under Secretary. Reference my 1427, December 3, 3
                    p.m. I now learn that Chinese reply to our document of November 27 will carry
                    proposal that on subject of coastal shipping and inland navigation the exchange
                    of notes shall include statement that should China later in any way extend the
                    right of inland navigation or participation in coastal trade to vessels <pb
                        facs="0399" n="389" xml:id="pg_389"/> of any third nation, such rights would
                    similarly be extended to American vessels.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
